  "notes": [
    "UC Santa Cruz students may complete one or more minors, provided they can finish all required coursework within their maximum enrollment terms and credit limits. Minors are recorded on the official transcript but do not appear on the diploma. Pursuing a minor is optional and should align with a student’s academic interests and career goals. Students do not apply for minors as part of their UC Santa Cruz admission application. Transfer students interested in a minor should reach out to the department that offers it for advising during their first quarter of enrollment.",
    "PREPARATION FOR THE MINOR The minor requires completion of six quarters of language study, or demonstration of an equivalent level of ability, and the following: LING 50: Introduction to Linguistics Effective the 2025–2026 academic year, UCSC no longer offers German or Portuguese language courses. Because this major requires intermediate-high proficiency in a non-English language (equivalent to two years of UCSC coursework), students who began these languages at their community college will be unable to continue them at UCSC. Please visit the Linguistics website to learn more about this minor. UC Santa Cruz General Catalog: Language Studies Minor Program Statement"
